":["English (Kent): variant of   Denn  .","French (mainly northern) and Walloon: probably a variant of <b>Dhenne</b>, a patronymic, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from <i>Henne</i>, a pet form of the personal names French <i>Henri</i>, Flemish <i>Hendrik</i> (see   Henry   1). Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Daine</b>, the feminine form of   Dain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denn","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Denne  , a habitational name from one or more of the numerous places in Kent and Sussex with names derived from Middle English <i>den</i> ‘woodland swine-pasture’ (Old English <i>denn</i>), such as Denne Manor in Chilham, Denne Hill in Kingston, and Denne Court in Woodnesborough (Kent); Denne Park in Horsham, Denne in Warnham, and Dann's Farm in Willingdon (Sussex).","English: possibly from a pet form of   Denis  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation.